 from ritual to the arts, from the sacrament to the sacramental. Investigating the relationship of the arts to the sacred, Schwartz returns to the primary meaning of "sacramental" as "sign making," noting that because the sign always points beyond itself, it participates in transcendence, and this evocation of transcendence, of mystery, is the work of a sacramental poetics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAesthetics, Modernx17th century. 0aAesthetics, Moderny17th century. 0aChristian poetry, EnglishxHistory and criticismxEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aChristian poetry, EnglishyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aChristianity and literaturexHistoryx17th centuryxEngland. 0aChristianity and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aEnglish poetryxHistory and criticismxEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aEnglish poetryyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aGod in literature. 0aRites and ceremonies in literature. 0aRitual in literaturexEngland. 0aRitual in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aReligion -- Philosophy of Religion. 4aReligion -- Theology. 7aRELIGION / Philosophy.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477955540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804779555423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804779555/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles